  "text": "## HTTP Client Retry and Timeout Logic\n\n**pkg/components/loki/lokihttp/config.go** defines the HTTP client configuration struct with two critical timeout/retry fields: `BackoffConfig backoff.Config` (line 19) for exponential backoff configuration and `Timeout time.Duration` (line 20) for request timeout duration.\n\n**pkg/components/loki/lokihttp/client.go** implements the main HTTP client with sophisticated retry and timeout handling. The `sendBatch()` method (line 290) creates a `backoff.New()` instance (line 299) using the configured `BackoffConfig`. The retry loop (lines 301-321) implements the retry logic by checking `backoff.Ongoing()` to determine if retries should continue, calling `backoff.Wait()` between attempts (line 315), and only retrying on 429 (rate limit) and 5xx server errors (lines 309-310). The `send()` method (line 330) applies request-level timeout via `context.WithTimeout(ctx, c.cfg.Timeout)` (line 331), and the HTTP client itself is configured with timeout at line 175: `c.client.Timeout = cfg.Timeout`. The critical `StopNow()` method (lines 375-380) immediately cancels all pending retries by calling `c.cancel()`, which stops the context used by the retry loop.\n\n**pkg/components/loki/lokihttp/fake.go** provides a test stub that implements the same `Client` interface with a no-op `StopNow()` method (line 39), allowing tests to simulate the client behavior without actual HTTP calls.\n\n## gRPC Client Retry and Timeout Logic\n\n**pkg/components/loki/lokigrpc/config.go** defines the gRPC configuration struct with `Retries uint` (line 9) for the maximum number of retry attempts and `Timeout time.Duration` (line 10) for request timeout duration.\n\n**pkg/components/loki/lokigrpc/client.go** implements gRPC client retry and timeout through two mechanisms. The `grpcRetryOption()` method (lines 82-88) configures gRPC retry policy using `grpcretry.UnaryClientInterceptor()` with `grpcretry.WithMax(c.cfg.Retries)` (line 85), which automatically retries failed gRPC calls up to the configured maximum. The `timeoutCtx()` method (lines 90-96) creates a context with timeout constraints: when `c.cfg.Timeout > 0`, it returns `context.WithTimeout(context.Background(), c.cfg.Timeout)` (line 92), otherwise it returns a cancellable context. This timeout context is used in the `Write()` method (lines 41-42) to enforce per-request timeout limits during log stream pushes."
